An Anonymous Epistle of Dido to Aeneas 33

By the life-giving principle of nature earth brings her changes and gladly summons the breezes of the fostering season; the fields are clothed again with the thick verdure of grass, the grain binds its shining tresses, and the advancing season does not cheat the ears of grain of their promise of a better harvest. Love alone cannot beguile its own weariness.

The weary plowman unfastens the yoke, and welcomes the night in answer to his prayers; grateful rest has power to refresh his toil, sleep, pervading his limbs, is not slow to restore his en- ergy, and at all times brings tovhusbandmen strength to care for their fields. Love alone cannot beguile its own weariness.

The seas by their inooming tides restore their shores
